CRITICAL ENGINEERING RULES

This native implementation is based on `/home/rahul/Documents/grapple-migration`.
Use those migration design files as the product/system source of truth, not the
old `showrunner-services` implementation.

Product bet:
- Grapple is a native video editor where the agent edits the composition graph,
  not final pixels.
- The core loop is: import media -> inspect timeline -> ask Steward for an edit
  -> apply canonical graph command -> preview evaluated result -> adjust exposed
  effect parameters -> render/export through the same shared core.
- Primary metric: time from intent to a correct, editable previewed graph change.
- Move aggressively toward the MVP product loop, but do not cut architectural
  corners or add breadth before the agent-edit loop is fast, correct, and editable.

Before implementing anything, ask:
Is this the simplest, minimal, cleanest, architecturally correct way to do it?

Before making any nontrivial implementation decision, state the decision explicitly
against these rules. If the clean decision is to rewrite/delete touched bad code,
do that instead of layering more code around it.

Do not stop to ask permission for ordinary reads, builds, tests, local edits,
profiling, or installing reasonable development tools. Ask only when the action
is destructive, requires product/business judgment, needs external credentials,
or would introduce a new architectural commitment.

If the issue comes from bad existing code, stop and rewrite/delete the bad code path.
Do not add support code, aliases, shims, fallbacks, compatibility layers, or compensating
conditionals to preserve bad architecture unless explicitly approved.

Core rules:
- Keep the minimum possible number of code paths.
- Prefer one canonical registry/state/flow over inferred or duplicated paths.
- Keep single canonical states. Do not maintain parallel source-of-truth state.
- Rewrite bad existing code when it is in the path of the work.
- Delete duplicate interpretation paths instead of adding conditionals.
- No backward compatibility layers unless explicitly requested.
- Make invalid old states fail loudly, or deliberately repair persisted state at the owning boundary.
- Do not patch symptoms. Trace to the exact wrong layer and fix that layer.
- Do not propose or add fallbacks as a solution. Find and fix the actual bug.
- Do not add validation as a substitute for understanding the broken invariant.
- Keep providers dumb: exact inputs in, exact provider calls out.
- Resolve product/system concepts at one clear boundary.
- UI shells display snapshots and send commands. UI does not own canonical state,
  render-plan construction, effect semantics, or project mutation.
- Project Core owns canonical graph state, TimelineIR, and RenderPlan construction requests.
- The local native app may have separate preview and final render shells.
- Preview and final render shells must be thin adapters over one shared render/runtime core.
- That shared render/runtime core consumes backend/core-produced RenderPlan.
- RenderPlan construction must stay pure: no script, shader, tracking, depth, or runtime execution.
- Render architecture is mode-agnostic: Grapple graph state -> TimelineIR projection -> RenderPlan -> shared local runtime/render core -> preview/final render shells.
- Do not duplicate graph traversal, render-plan interpretation, effect execution, dependency invalidation, media/cache policy, or runtime semantics between preview and final render.
- Preview and final render may differ in shell policy only: latency/quality, frame stepping, surfaces, encoding, and progress reporting.
- Do not put consumer-specific render language in agent-facing graph, script, shader, node, or tool contracts.
- Agent-authored effect code should target canonical graph/runtime APIs, not a specific render implementation.
- Agent-authored edits must expose user-editable parameters through canonical effect payload controls.
- Agent-authored edits must preserve user control: meaningful edit knobs belong in named, typed parameters, not hidden constants inside generated code.
- Do not let agents produce black-box edits when the same result can be represented as editable nodes and parameters.
- If a clean fix requires deleting old bloat in the touched path, delete it instead of supporting it.
- Do not build full future features early. Build the minimal correct foundation that keeps the later feature possible without putting that feature into the core path now.
- Keep future 3D, variants, model runtimes, and cloud collaboration possible by
  clean boundaries and typed data, not by implementing those features early.
- Support Linux, Windows, and macOS through portable C++/Qt/CMake and shared
  module boundaries. Do not add platform-specific code in core paths unless it
  is isolated behind a small named boundary and explicitly justified.
- Preview quality and export quality can have different shell policy, but they
  must not diverge in graph interpretation or runtime semantics.
- Use small, verified commits while moving quickly. Build and run relevant tests
  before committing; push clean verified chunks when a remote is configured.

Chat/conversation UI is fragile:
- Trace backend event emission -> persisted run events -> canonical conversation_state projection -> SSE payload -> frontend applyConversationState -> render.
- Do not fix backend event bugs in the UI.
- Do not fix UI projection bugs by suppressing statuses or hiding content.
- If delegated agent UI is wrong, verify delegated_run events existed in conversation_state before touching the renderer.
- Prefer deleting duplicate event emission and duplicate interpretation paths over adding more conditionals.
